# NEXUS - Home Operating System - Cursor Rules

## What This Is
A home operating system that runs on a Mac mini connected to a 65-inch TV. Controlled by phone. Powered by AI. Replaces smart home apps, dashboards, media queues, and scattered life signals with one unified ambient intelligent system.

## Architecture

### Three Layers
1. **TV (Display Layer)** - Next.js fullscreen UI at localhost:3000/tv. Always-on. No cursor. Designed for 65 inches.
2. **Phone (Controller)** - Mobile web UI at localhost:3000/controller. Controls TV via WebSocket. Drops content. Switches modes. Adds goals.
3. **Mac Mini (Engine)** - Hosts everything. Next.js app + WebSocket server + SQLite database.

### Running It
- `npm run dev` - starts the Next.js app (TV UI + API routes)
- `npm run ws` - starts the WebSocket server on port 8080 (run in separate terminal)
- TV opens localhost:3000 in fullscreen/kiosk Chrome
- Phone opens [mac-mini-ip]:3000/controller on the same network

## Tech Stack
- Next.js 14 (App Router)
- TypeScript
- Tailwind CSS
- SQLite via better-sqlite3 (local persistence)
- WebSocket via ws (phone-to-TV real-time)
- APIs: OpenWeatherMap (weather), Finnhub (stocks)

## Design Rules
- 65-INCH TV. Everything must be readable from 10 feet away.
- Massive typography. Outfit Ultra-Light for time/headings. DM Sans for body. JetBrains Mono for data labels.
- Dark mode only. Background #060608. No pure white text. Max opacity 0.95.
- Smooth transitions. Everything animates. Mode changes take 3 seconds to transition colors.
- Ambient feel. Floating orbs, breathing dots, gentle motion. It should feel alive, not static.
- No cursor. No scrollbars. No browser chrome. This is a TV OS, not a website.
- Mode colors: Morning #f59e0b, Focus #06b6d4, Home #10b981, Evening #8b5cf6, Weekend #f59e0b, Night #6366f1

## Mode Engine
Auto-switches based on time of day:
- 5-9 AM: Morning (stocks, goals, calendar)
- 9-5 PM weekdays: Focus (minimal, calendar, signals)
- 9-8 PM weekends: Weekend (sports, projects, recipes)
- 5-8 PM: Home (family schedule, recipes, deliveries)
- 8-11 PM: Evening (content queue, wind down)
- 11 PM-5 AM: Night (ultra minimal ambient)

Override via phone controller or keyboard (1-6 keys, 0 for auto).

## Data Flow
- Weather: GET /api/weather (cached 10min, OpenWeatherMap)
- Content: CRUD /api/content (SQLite, phone drops via POST)
- Goals: CRUD /api/calendar (SQLite, daily reset)
- Signals: CRUD /api/signals (SQLite, business alerts from Ralli/Toscana/Launch Pad)
- Stocks: GET /api/stocks (cached 5min, Finnhub)
- All APIs return mock data when no API keys configured. Always works.

## WebSocket Protocol
Phone and TV communicate via ws://localhost:8080. Message types:
- mode_switch: { type, mode } - switch TV mode
- mode_auto: { type } - return to auto mode
- content_drop: { type, url, title? } - drop content into queue
- content_play: { type, id } - play content on TV
- goal_toggle: { type, id } - check/uncheck goal
- goal_add: { type, label } - add new goal
- signal_dismiss: { type, id } - dismiss a signal
- refresh: { type } - force data refresh

## TV Views
- **Pulse** (default): Ambient screensaver. Giant clock. Weather. Signal ticker. Next event.
- **Dashboard** (press P): Two-column layout. Left: time, calendar, goals. Right: signals, content queue, mode tiles.
- **Content** (press C): Full-screen content browser overlay.

## File Structure
```
app/
  page.tsx              -> root (same as TV)
  layout.tsx
  globals.css
  tv/page.tsx           -> TV kiosk route
  controller/page.tsx   -> Phone controller
  api/
    weather/route.ts
    content/route.ts
    signals/route.ts
    calendar/route.ts
    stocks/route.ts
src/
  components/NexusTV.tsx -> Main TV UI component
  lib/
    db.ts               -> SQLite database layer
    mode-engine.ts      -> Mode determination logic
    ws-server.mjs       -> WebSocket server (standalone)
  hooks/
    useNexusSocket.ts   -> WebSocket client hook
    useNexusData.ts     -> Data fetching + polling hook
  types/
    nexus.ts            -> All TypeScript types
```

## What's Next (Phase 2)
- Wire NexusTV.tsx to useNexusData() hook instead of mock data
- Wire NexusTV.tsx to useNexusSocket() to receive phone commands
- Google Calendar API integration (real events)
- Home Assistant integration (lights, cameras, devices)
- Tailscale for remote access
- YouTube oEmbed for auto-fetching video titles/thumbnails on content drop
- Profile system (Rick vs Nicole, different tiles/signals per user)

## What's Next (Phase 3 - Intelligence Layer)
- Claude agent integration for suggested actions
- "Ask Nexus" voice/text command from phone
- Event-driven automation (e.g. if temp > 110, show AC alert)
- Content prioritization (AI suggests what to watch based on goals)
- Ralli AI / Launch Pad / Toscana live signal ingestion via webhooks

## SECURITY: Pre-Deploy Checklist
Before shipping code, verify:
1. No secrets in client code (API keys, tokens, passwords)
2. No auth tokens in localStorage (use httpOnly cookies)
3. All API routes have auth middleware
4. Rate limiting on public endpoints
5. CORS configured with explicit domains (no wildcard *)
6. All user input validated on backend
7. No dangerouslySetInnerHTML without sanitization
8. Environment variables for all config
9. npm audit shows no critical vulnerabilities
10. Supabase RLS enabled on every table
Run `./scripts/security-check.sh` before every deploy.

## Ralph (Autonomous Agent Loop)
This project has Ralph installed at scripts/ralph/.
To run autonomous builds:
1. Create a PRD: describe features as user stories in prd.json
2. Run: ./scripts/ralph/ralph.sh --tool claude 15
3. Ralph loops: pick task → implement → test → commit → next task
4. Review the feature branch when done
Each story should be small enough for one context window.

## Quality Checks (used by Ralph and manual deploys)
- `npx tsc --noEmit` (TypeScript)
- `npx next lint` (ESLint)
- `./scripts/security-check.sh` (Security)
- `npm test` (Tests, if they exist)
